Question: Does it hurt the horse to sit on it's back? To be in contact with the spine?
Answer:
Great question! If youâ€™re a balanced rider who maintains proper body position while balancing your own weight over the horseâ€™s 15th thoracic vertebra, allowing your weight to be supported on their latissimus dorsi by your thighs, dropping your weight down through your calves to your heels, you wonâ€™t hurt the horse at all! Thatâ€™s because this position aligns the riderâ€™s center of gravity with the horseâ€™s center of gravity, therefore making it easier to carry you. It also puts the most weight on their supporting back muscles (the lats) which are very strong.
  
  When riding in a saddle, in order not to cause the horse discomfort, you should still maintain correct body position as well as having the saddle placed between T8 and T18, so as not to put any weight on the floating ribs or  hinder the shoulder blade movement.

  You can also look at their body condition relative to their age. Older horses can sometimes look a bit thinner and droopier just like elderly people, but young horses shouldnâ€™t look that way. Itâ€™s also bad for them to be way too fat. You can also look at their hooves and see if theyâ€™re overgrown (indicating poor health and bad care from their person) or if theyâ€™re nicely maintained and help the horse bare weight evenly. You can look at their teeth, coat condition, eyes, lots of things can tell you if a horse is feeling well or not.

Question: Can a horse throw up or no
